column6: ['Society', 'Security and Conflict']

The odds of such an attack like this occurring in the next 5 years, I think is high, but not before September 2021 -- primarily and simply because that leaves very little time, less than two months from now.

Good overview on terrorist attacks in the U.S. in 2020 (or rather, lack thereof) : "So far, we’ve seen no foreign jihadist attacks on U.S. soil, and despite the grim headlines, the actual number of deaths from white supremacists and other domestic terrorists is small ... Data from the New America Foundation shows that zero Americans died from jihadist attacks in the United States this year. For 2020 so far, New America tallies eight terrorism deaths on U.S. soil, far fewer than the 30 Americans killed in 2019 ... Of course, 2020 could be an outlier year. Terrorists regularly plot, and sometimes they are caught and sometimes they succeed ... In 2000 and 2002, there were zero and four deaths, respectively. In 2001, there were 3,005 ... But U.S. policy has also played a role ... U.S. drone attacks and a global intelligence effort, among other lower-profile measures, have decimated the senior leadership of Islamic militant groups. In response, the jihadist movement has localized, focusing on civil wars in the Muslim world and spreading in to new areas in Africa, instead of coordinated attacks on the West." https://www.brookings.edu/blog/order-from-chaos/2020/12/24/2020-appears-to-be-a-good-year-for-counterterrorism/

Another indication that Islamic extremism, which is by far the most likely source of a CCTA in the U.S. directed/inspired by a foreign terrorist organization, continues to decline: according to the IEP’s new 2020 Global Terrorism Index report, "In 2019, deaths from terrorism fell for the fifth consecutive year, after peaking in 2014 ... ISIL’s strength and influence continued to decline ... The number of terrorist attacks attributed to the group [ISIL] also fell to the lowest level since it was formed, with 339 incidents attributed to the group in 2019." https://www.visionofhumanity.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/GTI-2020-web-1.pdf

With the travel restrictions due to the pandemic, it is very unlikely that a foreign terrorist organization is able to launch as CCTA in the United States. The FTOs are able to launch in other countries, such as in Europe (due to less restriction in border control), but no in the US.

Historically, homegrown far-right extremism poses the biggest threat to the US. From 1990-2019, when you include 9/11 there have been 47 events in the US motivated by Islamist extremism in the US. During that same period, according to the FBI website, 333 targets were either foiled or failed in the US. This means on average, there are roughly 16.5 terrorist attempts in the US. Given limited travel due to COVID, reduction in travel from Arab countries, and crackdown on the southern boarder, the likeliness of a terror attack is even less than before.
foreign terrorist organizations are on the ropes and the US is less of a target than it was 20 years ago. Domestic terrorism is much more likely.

Of the 13 complex coordinated terrorist attacks (CCTAs) that have occurred since 1990 (see my more detailed post for this question's sister question at [1]), there are five that have been either directed or inspired by a foreign terrorist organization (FTO) as designated by the US Department of State [2]. — February 26, 1993: World Trade Center bombing...https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1993_World_Trade_Center_bombing (FTO: al-Qa’ida) — September 11, 2001: September 11 attacks...https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/September_11_attacks (directed by FTO al-Qa’ida) — April 15, 2013: Boston Marathon bombing...https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston_Marathon_bombing (inspired by FTO al-Qa’ida) — May 3, 2015: Curtis Culwell Center attack...https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curtis_Culwell_Center_attack (directed by FTO Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant) — December 2, 2015: San Bernardino attack...https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_San_Bernardino_attack (inspired by FTO Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant)
